docs.abstract: A jury finds Derek Chauvin guilty.
docs.snippet: A jury finds Derek Chauvin guilty.
docs.lead_paragraph: Derek Chauvin, the former Minneapolis police officer, was found guilty yesterday on all three charges he faced in the death last year of George Floyd, capping one of the most-watched trials in the U.S. in recent memory. Follow live reactions.

docs.abstract: The chief judge of Hennepin County has set strict rules prohibiting the Floyd family from speaking to the news media outside the courtroom.
docs.snippet: The chief judge of Hennepin County has set strict rules prohibiting the Floyd family from speaking to the news media outside the courtroom.
docs.lead_paragraph: On Wednesday afternoon, when Charles McMillian, a witness to the death of George Floyd, broke down while recounting what he saw last May, Judge Peter Cahill called a short recess to allow Mr. McMillian to compose himself.

headline.main: When reporters try to speak with Floyd’s family outside the courtroom, sheriff’s deputies step in.

docs.abstract: Mr. Chauvin said the officers had to restrain Mr. Floyd because he would not stay in the back of a police car. “He was going crazy,” he said.
docs.snippet: Mr. Chauvin said the officers had to restrain Mr. Floyd because he would not stay in the back of a police car. “He was going crazy,” he said.
docs.lead_paragraph: A sergeant who supervised Derek Chauvin testified on Thursday that Mr. Chauvin and other police officers should have stopped holding George Floyd down once he became unresponsive.

headline.main: Officers should have stopped restraining George Floyd sooner, a former supervisor of Derek Chauvin’s testified.

docs.abstract: Sgt. Jonathan Mattingly, one of the officers involved in the fatal shooting, has a book deal with a small press, but its distributor, Simon & Schuster, in an unusual move, said it won’t ship it.
docs.snippet: Sgt. Jonathan Mattingly, one of the officers involved in the fatal shooting, has a book deal with a small press, but its distributor, Simon & Schuster, in an unusual move, said it won’t ship it.
docs.lead_paragraph: When the small, independent publisher Post Hill Press said on Thursday that it would release a book by one of the Louisville police officers who shot Breonna Taylor, the outrage practically burned down the internet. It took less than 12 hours for Simon & Schuster to announce that it would not distribute the book.

headline.main: Book by Officer Who Shot Breonna Taylor Is a New Test for Publishers
headline.print_headline: Controversial Title Presents Tightrope Act for a Publisher

docs.abstract: A special agent from the bureau testified at the Derek Chauvin trial on Wednesday. The agency has a range of responsibilities, including investigating all Minneapolis police killings.
docs.snippet: A special agent from the bureau testified at the Derek Chauvin trial on Wednesday. The agency has a range of responsibilities, including investigating all Minneapolis police killings.
docs.lead_paragraph: The second witness to take the stand in the trial of Derek Chauvin on Wednesday was a special agent with the Minnesota Bureau of Criminal Apprehension. Other employees of the agency are also expected to testify. So, what is it?

headline.main: What is the Minnesota Bureau of Criminal Apprehension, the agency that investigated George Floyd’s death?

docs.abstract: With the memory of last summer’s protests still fresh, some states have already ordered troops to be on standby in anticipation of large protests if there is an acquittal.
docs.snippet: With the memory of last summer’s protests still fresh, some states have already ordered troops to be on standby in anticipation of large protests if there is an acquittal.
docs.lead_paragraph: Cities across the country are preparing for protests as the jury in the murder trial of the former police officer Derek Chauvin entered its second day of deliberations on Tuesday. With the memory of last summer’s protests after George Floyd’s death still fresh, some states have ordered National Guard troops to be on standby in anticipation of large protests if there is an acquittal.

headline.main: National Guard troops are called to U.S. cities as the jury deliberates in the Chauvin trial.

docs.abstract: The Senate majority leader also discusses the filibuster, Joe Manchin and Democrats’ plan for 2022.
docs.snippet: The Senate majority leader also discusses the filibuster, Joe Manchin and Democrats’ plan for 2022.
docs.lead_paragraph: In his 100 days address this week, Joe Biden outlined his plans for a big, bold legislative agenda to come. He previewed a two-pronged economic package: the $2.25 trillion American Jobs Plan and the $1.8 trillion American Families Plan. He spoke about the need to pass universal background checks for firearms, comprehensive immigration reform, and the George Floyd Justice in Policing Act.

headline.main: How Chuck Schumer Plans to Win Over Trump Voters

docs.abstract: “That is not what we teach,” Chief Medaria Arradondo said of Mr. Chauvin kneeling on George Floyd for more than nine minutes.
docs.snippet: “That is not what we teach,” Chief Medaria Arradondo said of Mr. Chauvin kneeling on George Floyd for more than nine minutes.
docs.lead_paragraph: The chief of the Minneapolis Police Department testified on Monday that Derek Chauvin had “absolutely” violated department policies when he knelt on George Floyd for more than nine minutes in May, saying Mr. Chauvin “should have stopped” when Mr. Floyd was calling out for help.

headline.main: Derek Chauvin ‘absolutely’ violated policy, the Minneapolis police chief says.

byline.original: By Nicholas Bogel-Burroughs and John Eligon

docs.abstract: Every major broadcast and cable news network — and even ESPN — broke into regular programming on Tuesday for live coverage of the Derek Chauvin verdict.
docs.snippet: Every major broadcast and cable news network — and even ESPN — broke into regular programming on Tuesday for live coverage of the Derek Chauvin verdict.
docs.lead_paragraph: Every major broadcast and cable news network — and even ESPN — broke into regular programming on Tuesday for live coverage of the verdict, ensuring that millions of Americans watched in unison as a Minnesota jury found the former police officer Derek Chauvin guilty on all charges in the death of George Floyd.

headline.main: On TV, a tense wait, and then an emotional response.
headline.print_headline: Tense Wait, and an Emotional Response

docs.abstract: An expert testifying for the defense said Mr. Chauvin was justified in pinning George Floyd under his knee. He contradicted numerous experts called by prosecutors, including the police chief of Minneapolis.
docs.snippet: An expert testifying for the defense said Mr. Chauvin was justified in pinning George Floyd under his knee. He contradicted numerous experts called by prosecutors, including the police chief of Minneapolis.
docs.lead_paragraph: For the first time in the trial of the former police officer Derek Chauvin, a witness explicitly defended his actions when he knelt on George Floyd for nine and a half minutes.
